{"questionId":"13919694","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>The assumption that the value of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>g</mi></math> is constant is not correct. It can be shown that</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>g</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>98</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>14</mn></msup></mrow><msup><mfenced><mrow><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>41</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>6</mn></msup><mo>-</mo><mi>s</mi></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac></math>.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:left;\">Hence, the new model is given by</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>v</mi><mfrac><mrow><mo>d</mo><mi>v</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>d</mo><mi>s</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>98</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>14</mn></msup></mrow><msup><mfenced><mrow><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>41</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>6</mn></msup><mo>-</mo><mi>s</mi></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>8</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfenced><msup><mi>v</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math>.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:left;\">When <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>s</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math>, it is known that <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>v</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>10</mn></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Hence, find the value of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>v</mi></math> predicted by this model, as <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>s</mi></math> tends to infinity.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>s</mi><mo>→</mo><mo>∞</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>k</mi><mi>s</mi></mrow></msup><mo>→</mo><mn>0</mn></math>&nbsp; &nbsp;<strong>OR</strong>&nbsp; &nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mo>d</mo><mi>v</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>d</mo><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math>&nbsp; &nbsp;<strong>OR</strong>&nbsp; &nbsp;graph/table&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><msub><mi>v</mi><mi>max</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mfrac><mi>g</mi><mi>k</mi></mfrac></msqrt><mo>=</mo></mrow></mfenced><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>350</mn><mo> </mo><mfenced><mrow><mi>m</mi><msup><mi>s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p style=\"text-align:right;\"><em><strong>[2 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"13919694","referenceCode":"23N.3.AHL.TZ0.1ciii","subjectId":"51-dp-mathematics-applications-and-interpretation","title":"Hence, find the value of v predicted by this model, as s tends to infinity.","paper":"3","level":"HL","questionNumber":"iii","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 2]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 2—Functions","Topic 5—Calculus","Topic 5—Calculus","AHL 5.11—Indefinite integration, reverse chain, by substitution","Topic 5—Calculus","AHL 5.14—Setting up a DE, solve by separating variables","Topic 2—Functions","SL 2.6—Modelling skills"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":3}
